BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:PdkD7Tf4SZKtgGPnjdGom
SUMMARY:Inaugural Albers Marketing Alumni Mentorship Mixer
DTSTAMP:20260307T070346Z
DTSTART:20260312T190000Z
DESCRIPTION:Join fellow Seattle University Albers School Marketing alumni f
	or an engaging virtual conversation designed to strengthen connections and
	 support your continued professional growth.\n\n \n\nThis interactive sess
	ion will feature a facilitated Q&A with industry leaders Katie Milburn \\(
	’14\\)\, Manager of Internal Recruiting at Salesforce\, and Lindsey Davis\
	, Senior Manager of Strategy and Operations\, People eXperience and Techno
	logy \\(PXT\\) at AWS. Together\, they will share insights on career devel
	opment\, leadership\, navigating change\, and building meaningful professi
	onal pathways in today’s evolving workplace.\n\n \n\nFollowing the moderat
	ed discussion\, participants will move into small breakout rooms for more 
	personalized conversations with industry mentors and Albers faculty. This 
	format offers a unique opportunity to ask questions\, exchange ideas\, and
	 connect with peers in a more informal setting.\n\n \n\nWhether you are ea
	rly in your career\, considering your next move\, or looking to expand you
	r professional network\, this event is designed to provide practical advic
	e\, fresh perspectives\, and renewed connection to the Albers Marketing co
	mmunity.\n\n \n\nWe look forward to seeing you online!\n\nhttps://seatoday
	.6amcity.com/events/#/details/inaugural-albers-marketing-alumni-mentorship
	-mixer/18260238/2026-03-12T00\n\nFrom SEAtoday - All Events
URL:https://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/inaugural-albers-marketin
	g-alumni-mentorship-mixer/18260238/2026-03-12T00
X-CALRIPPER-SOURCE:seatoday-all
CATEGORIES:SEAtoday - All Events
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
DURATION:PT13H
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:3t4MOZvMWNxBBRRSmoflh
SUMMARY:Restoration Event | Native Plant Nursery
DTSTAMP:20260307T070346Z
DTSTART:20260312T190000Z
DESCRIPTION:Monthly Native Plant Nursery Work Party\n\nCalling all native  
	plant lovers! We're looking for volunteers to join us each month to help  
	us care for the plants in our native plant nursery. Every year we host a c
	 ouple thousand native plants in the nursery until they're ready to be put
	  in the ground in parks across the island. \n\nThis will be a great oppor
	 tunity to learn more about native plants\, learn about basic plant care\,
	 and help us ensure our plants healthy before being put in their new homes
	. \n\nTasks may include: weeding potted plants\, up-potting or repotting n
	ative plants\, plant organizing\, plant propagation\, weeding gravel areas
	\, tool care\, nursery pot maintenance\, and watering.\n\nWhen: Thursday\,
	  March 12th\, 12pm-2pm \\(join us on your lunch break!\\)\n\nWhere: Luthe
	r Burbank Park\, Caretakers building \n\nWhat to bring: Dress for the weat
	her in clothes you don't mind getting dirty \\(think: long pants\, boots o
	r sneakers\\). Bring water. Small snacks\, gloves\, and tools will be prov
	ided.\n\nRegistration: https://volunteersignup.org/B4AFB\n\n\n\n \n\nOpens
	 in new w indow\n\nPDF Download\n\nWord Download\n\nExcel Download\n\nPowe
	rPoint Dow nload\n\nDocument Download\n\nhttps://seatoday.6amcity.com/even
	ts/#/details/restoration-event-native-plant-nursery/18066422/2026-03-12T00
	\n\nFrom SEAtoday - All Events
URL:https://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/restoration-event-native-
	plant-nursery/18066422/2026-03-12T00
X-CALRIPPER-SOURCE:seatoday-all
CATEGORIES:SEAtoday - All Events
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
DURATION:PT2H
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:nuFp9Hd0vBqr4aC585n9y
SUMMARY:Susan Meiselas: Crossings
DTSTAMP:20260307T070346Z
DTSTART:20260312T190000Z
DESCRIPTION:First presented at the Art Institute of Chicago in 1990\, this 
	exhibition by Susan Meiselas intertwines documentary photographs of Centra
	l America during the 1970s and 1980s \\(from Nicaragua and El Salvador\\) 
	along with panoramic images from the US/Mexico border taken in 1989. Addit
	ional photographs of the US/Mexico border taken in 2018 are also featured 
	in a site-specific gallery installation. The exhibition invites viewers to
	 see immigration in the context of economic and political crises in the re
	gion.\n\nToday\, the work feels newly urgent. US immigration enforcement h
	as expanded through militarization and constant surveillance\, with leader
	s using fear-driven language to divide communities and legitimize brutal f
	orms of control.\n\nThese photographs ask us to look carefully\, to recogn
	ize familiar patterns\, and to hold on to our shared humanity across the g
	lobe. People move in search of safety\, possibility\, and a better life fo
	r their families\, which is a universal hope that crosses borders\, genera
	tions\, and time.\n\nhttps://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/susan-m
	eiselas-crossings/17977024/2026-03-12T00\n\nFrom SEAtoday - All Events
URL:https://seatoday.6amcity.com/events/#/details/susan-meiselas-crossings/
	17977024/2026-03-12T00
LOCATION:Photographic Center Northwest (PCNW)\, 900 12th Ave.\, Seattle\, W
	A
X-CALRIPPER-SOURCE:seatoday-all
CATEGORIES:SEAtoday - All Events
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
DURATION:PT9H
END:VEVENT
